Good idea! Here’s a simple snippet that uses `std::process::Command` to run an SSH tunnel. Note, however, you’ll need to handle arguments properly and ensure that sensitive credentials are not hard-coded in the script. I also suggest using environment variables or config files for credentials rather than plain strings.

```rust
use std::process::{Command, Stdio};

fn main() {
    let output = Command::new("ssh")
        .args(&["-L", "8080:localhost:5432"])
        .arg("user@remote.example.com")
        .stdout(Stdio::piped())
        .stderr(Stdio::piped())
        .output()
        .expect("Failed to execute ssh command");

    if output.status.success() {
        println!("SSH tunnel started: {}", String::from_utf8_lossy(&output.stdout));
    } else {
        eprintln!("Error starting SSH tunnel: {}", String::from_utf8_lossy(&output.stderr));
    }
}
```

Ah, good question! You just pass in additional `-L` flags as arguments. Here’s an example where I add two port mappings:

```rust
use std::process::{Command, Stdio};

fn main() {
    let output = Command::new("ssh")
        .args(&[
            "-L", "8080:localhost:5432",
            "-L", "8081:localhost:6789",
        ])
        .arg("user@remote.example.com")
        .stdout(Stdio::piped())
        .stderr(Stdio::piped())
        .output()
        .expect("Failed to execute ssh command");

    if output.status.success() {
        println!("SSH tunnel started: {}", String::from_utf8_lossy(&output.stdout));
    } else {
        eprintln!("Error starting SSH tunnel: {}", String::from_utf8_lossy(&output.stderr));
    }
}
```
